HEADWORD: Arcadia
<hw>Ar*ca"di*a</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Arcadia</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mountainous and
picturesque district of Greece, in the heart of the Peloponnesus, whose
people were distinguished for contentment and rural happiness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Any region or scene of simple pleasure and
untroubled quiet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the cow is, there is <qex>Arcadia</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Burroughs.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Arcadic</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Arcadian</ent>⟦br⟧
